text: Yeah, that's right. I was looking at all the guests that you hosted so far and I was quite flattered to see that I was the first sell-side quant, so thanks a lot for that. I guess there are, first of all, on the sell side, you find a lot of quants, but there are more pricing quants, risk modeling quants. They have a role in the bank as to help the bank to hedge products or design products. They're very much product-orientated, especially at Soccision. What I'm doing is much more in line with what my clients do on the buy side, so that's something that I would call investment quants. As investment quants, we're interested into the dynamics in the markets, but not the dynamics that allows you to price structured and complex products, but more into the dynamics of the market that would allow you to make money at some point. In that sense, although I'm working on the sell side, my job is very similar. To what the buy side quant would be interesting in. I'm very much focusing on statistical learning, how to use statistical models to calibrate systematic strategies, how do you think about portfolio location while taking into account historical correlations, left tails behavior, distributions, historical distribution, et cetera. I'd say an investment quant is, if you put it in a model, it's a very simple model. It's a very simple model. It's a very simple modeling language. An investment quant would be very much interested into modeling the historical distribution or the historical measure, while sell side quants, more interested into pricing, would be more interesting in modeling the risk neutral measure. In my work, I'm more interested into the historical measure. Even though my job resembles very much the job of a buy side, there's still differences there because I'm not managing money, and I guess that's the way it is. That's the main point. As I stated to start with, my views are not linked to any company's views or any AUM, basically. As such, I'm more, I guess my role with respect to my clients is more of a consulting role, investment advisor role, investment advisory. In this perspective, it gives me the opportunity and the quite unique chance of looking at the right range of investments use case. Because I'm not working for only one investment manager, I'm working for potentially all our clients. That gives me exposure to a lot of different business cases. Every asset manager out there have their own institutional mandates, their own investment constraints. The great thing about being a sell side quant is that you get a little bit exposure about what the clients are potentially doing.
